app.comment: Control a Sphero via Bluetooth. Requires the TouchDevelop Windows Phone App v3.11, or another Bluetooth-enabled TouchDevelop platform, and a paired Sphero.
Control a Sphero via Bluetooth. Requires the TouchDevelop app v3.1 for Windows Phone, or another Bluetooth-enabled TouchDevelop platform, and a paired Sphero.

reMNmcO2sSXluHIkZCXN4V6T.text: Orders the Sphero to sleep for a given number of seconds

m7Dgi45oywtvApZu02S7CANf.text: Gets the location of the Sphero with respect to the locator origin

uY9Y5tyROPGAsCF2ylcPKxmR.text: This command is used to verify both a solid data link and that the Sphero is awake and dispatching commands.

o47aBFrp7KepdBMa6ZHpb4EY.text: This library allows to control a Sphero that has been paired via Bluetooth. Learn more about Sphero at http://www.gosphero.com/.

DtJJ1N2DqalGHXYOz7pSDdu3.text: This library is still under construction.

N5bUbPynu3X0q0g0Zz6sp2rq.text: Commands a new reference heading in degrees. The ball will respond immediately to this command if stabilization is enabled.

ckaip2Z45DI7c5K2nL4gyclA.text: This turns on or off the internal stabilization of Sphero. You will want to disable stabilization when using Sphero as an external input controller or to save battery power.

xj8q4bsO1tBbGX8E8B9yeeJa.text: Allows to take over one or both of the motor output values, instead of having the stabilization system control them. Each motor (left and right) requires a mode (`off`, `forward`, `reverse`, `brake`) and a power value from 0 to 255. This command will disable stabilization if both modes aren't `ignore` so you will need to re-enable it once you are done.

r4f2V6g2bfw2f4VCCbpJHdWg.text: Sets the color of the LED.

WmCr2hf9HXu5MXKyy4805vXi.text: Sets the color of the LED.

x3V7WLWWEKoHVnwCaFV4PK6R.text: Turns on or off the tail light.

o2PqD4WbwP11t90oPyN7wEw4.text: Connects to a Sphero through Bluetooth.

bl2krjFsBy9qUN12H2ifzUs3.text: To get started, you must call the `connect` action and wait on it. The connection might fail
To get started, you must call the `connect` action and wait on it. The connection might fail.
To get started, you must call the `connect` action and wait on it. The connection might fail. The library uses the `log` to display diagnostic messages.

EKSo7sA56rfKjnaJfufgXxk4.text: You can ping the Sphero to make sure it is properly connected.

CHqOSXXrPE02ogUSbeHNqHKJ.text: You can also use `roll to` to specify a particular coordinate to roll to. The Sphero uses sensors to estimate its position with respect to the calibrated origin. Below we have the Sphero draw a square.

rg424Qvv2f4uMIoucWvwkQ4k.text: Commands the Sphero to roll with a given heading and speed

iVOxwELgfcs5qZ2Rd9e1CUuR.text: Uses the locator to roll the Sphero to a particular location with respect to the current calibration.

xeg916dnEsCDSX4cbCOtYXUD.text: You can change the color of the LED.

ZjZDx6COdaShdnnslWvIPydc.text: You can set the heading of the Sphero in degrees. Let's have it turn left, then come back to 0 degrees.

J54GHYChNPokCDF7vqUemTUr.text: You can command the ball to roll with a given heading.
You can command the ball to roll at a given speed.

x9adkcVCBZKJ9kje65I8LhXD.text: Sets the intensity of the tail light from 0 off to 1 on.

v4sADfkLVYjwIJH80fVsK5EI.text: Brings the Sphero to a stop while keeping a heading.

qDyzB6Bxa3Do4aErQWX3R3re.text: Disconnects the current Sphero if any

F53RMSPlAjhK9OKcVu0EpwNC.text: Indicates if currently connected to a Sphero
